<subSubSection id="D776A57D30882A1958FDD5D1E08AEE92" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="966CA7F82A1BCDDD24418E8F36F06F7C" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="64300DAFC95688F3D43A52805AE15658" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">
Given 
<normalizedToken id="0F5E0960A4990B5E5AAAEC5F8D26BA45" originalValue="Corner’s">Corner's</normalizedToken>
original description almost totally lacked any microscopic information, we present a full description here based on the holotype plus two more recent collections from roughly the same location, both collected by E. Horak. Morphologically, this species most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="D8D48298B81BE0FB12E32AD289E25568" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Psathyrellaceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma angustilamellatum" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="angustilamellatum">
<emphasis id="744451A2BFC8410E3FCF2B227A47D772" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">Hebeloma angustilamellatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, originally described from the Yunnan province of China (
<bibRefCitation id="1024CE40874BD74DDF294FC683E49A2B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756205003758" author="Yang, ZL" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" pagination="1259 - 1267" refId="B55" refString="Yang, ZL, Matheny, PB, Ge, Z-W, Slot, JC, Hibbett, DS, 2005. New Asian species of the genus Anamika (Euagarics, hebelomatoid Clade) based on morphology and ribosomal DNA sequences. Mycological Research 109: 1259 - 1267, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756205003758" title="New Asian species of the genus Anamika (Euagarics, hebelomatoid Clade) based on morphology and ribosomal DNA sequences." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756205003758" volume="109" year="2005">Yang et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
) and also recorded from northern Thailand and Laos (Table 
<tableCitation id="5DD0F4583363683C48C866FBCB24AAC6" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Sequences used in the analysis. Herbarium abbreviations follow Index Herbariorum and are given in capital letters followed by a space or hyphen and the herbarium number. Private collections are indicated by the lack of a space between the letters and numbers. MO refers to https: // mushroomobserver. org /" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/90F8B886FD97081280CDD2D7C4B7B3BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" tableUuid="90F8B886FD97081280CDD2D7C4B7B3BE">1</tableCitation>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="598C9A0D4C417B2A88C57EBE70BA01AC" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. ML topology of concatenated ITS and MCM 7 sequences of Hebeloma and Alnicola. Flammula alnicola is used for rooting purposes. Bootstrap support based on 500 replicates and posterior probabilities based on a BI analysis are indicated at the branches. Assignment of species to sections follows Beker et al. (2016). Sequences in red are from Malaysian collections discussed in this paper. T indicates type collections. Thick branches indicate full support. AS - Asia, EU - Europe, NA - North America, O - Oceania, gr. - group." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.77.57394.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/502270" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">1</figureCitation>
), from which it can be distinguished morphologically by the very strongly ornamented spores (O4), conspicuous even without immersion (those of 
<taxonomicName id="E191A0ADD7D05F6384ECE6672C171D7C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. angustilamellatum" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustilamellatum">
<emphasis id="A052D219FDE60EC9790B8771FC91D100" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">H. angustilamellatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are O3, so distinctly ornamented but not conspicuous without immersion) and the less conspicuous annulus on the fibrillose stipe of mature basidiomes (
<taxonomicName id="05F6E736D97CAE9BCCA69F4725F64D91" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. angustilamellatum" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustilamellatum">
<emphasis id="EB91514EF764346C3C6EEDBE77C5F16C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">H. angustilamellatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a more persistent annulus, always present, and a stipe, with scattered fibrillose scales, consistently present.) Phylogenetically, based on ITS and 
<emphasis id="100AAC80CE2A3AF063F6D55996F3DF82" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">MCM7</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5D2469D67243EBCBE5C1326CF11D01EA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. flavidifolium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="flavidifolium">
<emphasis id="0BF78D67D2A0AD07FE4837F4232E128B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">H. flavidifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a sister species of 
<taxonomicName id="0FE05B02203ADD1CDD474FCD3C0F8523" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. ifeleleretorum" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ifeleleretorum">
<emphasis id="2FE9A7FBB9C57FC5583B645F3CB39CDF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">H. ifeleleretorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described from Samoa, but all three form a cluster in Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5D4DB1CC94B8FC3E6E7FA8E7F8638AB9" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. ML topology of concatenated ITS and MCM 7 sequences of Hebeloma and Alnicola. Flammula alnicola is used for rooting purposes. Bootstrap support based on 500 replicates and posterior probabilities based on a BI analysis are indicated at the branches. Assignment of species to sections follows Beker et al. (2016). Sequences in red are from Malaysian collections discussed in this paper. T indicates type collections. Thick branches indicate full support. AS - Asia, EU - Europe, NA - North America, O - Oceania, gr. - group." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.77.57394.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/502270" pageId="0" pageNumber="117">1</figureCitation>
that received full posterior probability and 92% bootstrap support.
</paragraph>
